{[show NS]

South is to play 6NT. West leads the \SK.

Make a Plan, then click NEXT. [NEXT]

[show NESW]

[clear-commentary]

You have 11 winners; 1 \S, 2 \Hs, 4 \Ds and 4 \Cs. If you can make a trick with the \SJ all will be well. But if not, as long as West holds the \SQ, which is almost a certainty, you will be able to squeeze him in \Ss and \Hs. 

The first thing you should do is to duck the \SK. If West foolishly plays another \S your troubles are over. But he doesn't, he plays the \HQ instead which you win with dummy's \HK.  [NEXT]

[PLAY N:S2,N:HK,E:S5,E:HT,S:S3,S:H4,W:SK,W:HQ]

[clear-commentary]

Even though West didn't play a second \S your first round duck served a very important purpose - it rectified the count for your squeeze.

Next play off your 4 \D winners, discarding a small \H from your hand. [NEXT]

[PLAY N:DA,N:DQ,N:D7,N:D4,E:D9,E:D8,E:D5,E:D2,S:H6,S:DK,S:DJ,S:D6,W:H5,W:H2,W:DT,W:D3]

[clear-commentary]

You are now zeroing in on West.

Play the \CK, \CJ, then over to your \CQ. [NEXT]

[showcards N:S7,S4,HA,H3 E:S9,S8,S6,C8 S:SA,SJ,H7,CA W:SQ,ST,HJ,H9]

[PLAY N:CK,N:CJ,N:C3,E:C6,E:C4,E:C2,S:CQ,S:CT,S:C7,W:H8,W:C9,W:C5]

[clear-commentary]

Here is the layout after the 3 \C plays. Everybody followed suit except West who discarded a \H (unhappily, it seemed). 

When you now play your \CA, discarding a \S from dummy, West is squeezed.

If he discards the \ST, then his \SQ will fall underneath your \SA, establishing your \SJ.

But if he instead throws the \H9, both of dummy's \Hs will become winners.}
[Play "W"]SK

