[Student "S"]
{[show NS]

South is to play 6\D. West leads the \HK.

Make a Plan, then click NEXT. [NEXT]

[show NESW]

[clear-commentary]

You have 11 winners; 1 \S, 1 \H, 6 \Ds and 3 \Cs.

At first things look hopeless, but remember this is a lesson on squeeze plays. From the opening lead you know that West must hold the \HQ. If he also holds the \SK you will be able to squeeze him in \Hs and \Ss.

You let the \HK win, (hoping he will play another \H), but he plays a small trump instead which you win in your hand. [NEXT]

[PLAY N:H2,N:D4,E:H3,E:DT,S:H4,S:DA,W:HK,W:D2]

[clear-commentary]

Pull one more round of trumps, then unblock the \SA.

Then take your 3 \C winners, ending in your hand. [NEXT]

[PLAY N:S2,N:D6,N:CK,N:CQ,N:C2,E:S6,E:S4,E:C8,E:C6,E:C3,S:SA,S:DK,S:CA,S:C7,S:C4,W:S3,W:D3,W:CT,W:C9,W:C5]

[clear-commentary]

Now play \DQ, \DJ, \D9. Discard the \S5 from dummy on the third \D.  [NEXT]

[showcards N:SQ,HA,H8 E:SJ,S9,H9 S:HJ,H7,D7 W:SK,HQ,HT]

[PLAY N:S5,N:DQ,N:D8,E:S8,E:H5,E:CJ,S:DJ,S:D9,S:D5,W:ST,W:S7,W:H6]

[clear-commentary]

West could afford to throw 2 \Ss and a \H on your \D plays.

But when you play the \D7 he is squeezed.

He cannot dump his \SK because you would throw the \H8 and dummy would be high.

So he will discard the \H10 instead. At this point you know that the \SQ is worthless so you discard it. You win the final two tricks with the \HA and \HJ.}
[Play "W"]HK

