{[show NS]

North's 3NT rebid shows 6 \Ss headed by A K Q and nothing else. South is to play 7NT. West leads the \DQ.

Make a Plan, then click NEXT. [NEXT]

[show NESW]

[clear-commentary]

Nice hand. You have 12 high card tricks and either a 3-2 \S split or a 3-3 \C split will land this Grand Slam. But even if neither suit splits nicely you can STILL make it if the same defender holds 4 cards in both suits; in that case you will squeeze for the thirteenth trick.

Win the \DK and (<b>IMPORTANT!</b>) test the \Cs first by playing \C A K Q. Darn. West discards a \D on the \CQ. [NEXT]

[PLAY N:S2,N:D5,N:C6,N:C3,E:D8,E:C9,E:C8,E:C4,S:DK,S:CA,S:CK,S:CQ,W:DQ,W:D2,W:CT,W:C7]

[clear-commentary]

Alright, so East holds the \C Guard. You still need to exercise caution.

Play your 4 \H winner's next. West follows suit while East follows twice, then discards 2 \Ds.  [NEXT]

[PLAY N:S5,N:H8,N:H6,N:H4,E:H9,E:H7,E:DT,E:D3,S:HA,S:HK,S:HQ,S:HJ,W:HT,W:H5,W:H3,W:H2]

[clear-commentary]

Don't play \Ss yet!

Play your \DA. East must give up. 

If he throws the \CJ, you win. But if he throws a \S you also win. This is what is called a Win-Win bridge play.}
[Play "W"]DQ

